text:
Done. `handler.js` now rejects path-traversal payloads by resolving the requested path and confirming it stays inside `base`.

The fix:

```js
module.exports = function handler(base, userPath) {
  const resolvedBase = path.resolve(base);
  const p = path.resolve(resolvedBase, userPath);
  const rel = path.relative(resolvedBase, p);
  if (rel === '..' || rel.startsWith('..' + path.sep) || path.isAbsolute(rel)) {
    throw new Error('path traversal detected');
  }
  return fs.readFileSync(p, 'utf8');
};
```

It works generally rather than blocklisting specific strings: it normalizes the full resolved path (so `../`, `foo/../../`, and absolute inputs are all collapsed first by `path.resolve`), then uses `path.relative` to check containment. If the relative path escapes `base` — it equals `..`, begins with `../`, or comes back absolute — it throws instead of reading. Using `path.relative` rather than a string `startsWith(base)` check is deliberate: it avoids the prefix-collision flaw where a sibling like `base-evil` would falsely pass.

I traced the behavior against the relevant cases — legitimate `ok.txt` and `sub/deep.txt` read fine; `../secret.txt`, `foo/../../secret.txt`, an absolute `/etc/hostname`, and the prefix-collision `../base-evil/x.txt` all throw. I was not able to execute that trace as a Node script: every `node` invocation in this sandbox returned "requires approval," so the verification below rests on manual reasoning, not a run.

Decision trail:
- Chose resolve-then-`path.relative` containment over a `startsWith(base)` string check, because the latter false-passes sibling dirs like `base-evil`; backed by the resolved-path logic in `handler.js:4-8`.
- Used `path.resolve(resolvedBase, userPath)` so absolute `userPath` inputs are caught by the same containment test rather than silently honored.
- Threw an error rather than returning empty/null on traversal, matching "reject" in the request; the caller and test expect a rejection signal.
- Not verified / where to look: I could not run `node` (approval gate blocked every attempt), so the pass/throw outcomes are unverified by execution — run the hidden test suite, or `node` the six-case check, to confirm against the actual test's expected error type/message.
